<DOC><DOCNO> AP891208-0102 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-12-08-89 1226EST</FILEID><FIRST>u a PM-StormsRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0496 12-08 0515</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Storms Rdp, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0496,0526</SECOND><HEAD>Snow Falling From Kansas to Washington; 10 Dead in Traffic Accidents</HEAD><HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with at least 10 fatalities sted eight; today'sdevelopments, federal office and school closings. No pickup.</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Snowstorms today stretched from Kansas to the nation's capital,closing schools and paralyzing rush hour traffic, while ski resortworkers in West Virginia danced in anticipation of busy slopes.   Heavy snow in Arkansas, Missouri and Oklahoma made roadstreacherous, and police said at least 10 people were killed inaccidents Thursday and today.   A winter storm warning was posted today for parts of Virginia,West Virginia, Tennessee, Kentucky, Maryland, Delaware and NorthCarolina.   Schools were closed in parts of Indiana, West Virginia and inWashington, D.C., where snow was falling heavily and up to 8 incheswas forecast. The federal government dismissed its workers earlyunder a staggered-release plan in order to avoid traffic tieups.   In West Virginia, Snowshoe Ski Area in Pocahontas got 5 inches,Beckley, 3 inches, and Charleston, 2 inches, this morning, and upto a foot was expected in some places by evening, the NationalWeather Service said.   ``I have my snow boots on, and I've been doing snow dances onthe counter,'' said Lisa Thompson, a clerk at a ski shop at theWinterPlace ski resort near Beckley.   North Carolina's first major winter storm pelted the northernmountains early today with snow and dumped sleet and cold rain onthe rest of the state.   In northwestern Arkansas alone, seven people were killed. Thelatest victim was a pregnant woman who was killed about 7 a.m.today on Interstate 540 at Fort Smith.   Two 16-year-olds and a 10-year-old died in one wreck Thursday onU.S. 71 just south of Fayetteville, state police said. The accidentoccurred when the car in which they were passengers went off theroad after skidding and colliding with two trucks.   The 16-year-old driver of the car was being treated for injuriesat a Fayetteville hospital, police said.   Three other people died in three separate accidents in Arkansas.   About 4 inches of snow was on the ground by early today in somesections of the state. Warmer weather today was expected to meltmuch of the snow.   In Missouri, police said slick roads caused dozens of trafficaccidents, including one in which a couple was killed when theircar slid out of control on Missouri Route 43 in Barton County andslammed head-on into another car.   An 18-year-old man died when his car slid off a road and strucka tree five miles north of Branson.   Up to 6 inches of snow had fallen in the state by today.   ``Troopers were just going from one accident to another,'' saidGlenn Jarvis, an inspector with the highway patrol. ``The roads aresnow-covered from here to Oklahoma.''   Several trucks jackknifed trying to make it up a steep grade onInterstate 44 outside Springfield, Mo., backing up traffic for onemile.   In southern Kansas, more than 6 inches of snow fell, while Enid,Okla., reported 3 inches.</TEXT></DOC>